Fearful lest his work should assume the character of a chronicle, he fell into the opposite extreme, and frequently relatas circumstances without stating the exact year in which they· occurred. He did this either in imitation of the Roman writers, or for the purpose of avoiding the difficulty of fixing each transaction to a parv ticular year, there being such frequent discre- pancies on those points in the sources whence he derived his information. It was not the custom of the Saxons to be very exactas to dates in their annals. In some copies of that invaluable relic-the Saxon Chronicle-events are recorded as occurring in given years, while in other copies the same events are referred to different years.
